00:26:22.710 --> 00:26:28.430
Now the Macintosh has a concept of
a resource fork in the file system.

00:26:28.430 --> 00:26:35.269
And the resource fork is really a way
to store meta data, or data about data.

00:26:35.269 --> 00:26:43.539
Now some file formats, like MP3s, or maybe
the pictures that you shoot on your camera,

00:26:43.539 --> 00:26:49.779
MP3s got ID3information tags, a
photo is going to have EXIF information about that,

00:26:49.779 --> 00:26:53.430
information about when that picture was
taken, maybe the exposure information.

00:26:53.430 --> 00:26:56.100
And a lot of times that information
is stored right in the file.

00:26:56.099 --> 00:27:04.059
Well a lot of vendors use a separate resource fork to store
that information instead of putting it right in the file.

00:27:04.059 --> 00:27:10.379
So on the Mac you have this concept of the data portion
of your file, and then the resource portion of that file.

00:27:10.380 --> 00:27:13.750
But in the Mac all you see is a single file.

00:27:13.750 --> 00:27:19.819
And what happens is when you move that file to what
we call a foreign file system, that's when you,

00:27:19.819 --> 00:27:24.939
the Macintosh has to take some
maneuvers to get that file into a format

00:27:24.940 --> 00:27:28.180
that can be properly be stored on that external file system.

00:27:28.180 --> 00:27:31.110
And generally that means using the Apple double file format.

00:27:31.109 --> 00:27:35.779
Now Apple, what Apple double will do is it'll
take the resource and fork and the data fork,

00:27:35.779 --> 00:27:38.369
and it will actually create two files on that file system.

00:27:38.369 --> 00:27:43.699
And that's commonly why you'll see the dot
underscore file, possibly when you're looking

00:27:43.700 --> 00:27:47.080
