00:30:22.309 --> 00:30:28.019
Now we're going to take a look at file system
domains, and the concept of bringing some structure

00:30:28.019 --> 00:30:30.190
to the typical file hierarchy that you'll see.

00:30:30.190 --> 00:30:38.029
Now what this does is it really
organizes the file system by scope.

00:30:38.029 --> 00:30:42.569
And what I mean by that is part of, you'll
see the four domains there, a user domain,

00:30:42.569 --> 00:30:47.200
a computer domain, the system domain, and a network domain.

00:30:47.200 --> 00:30:55.920
Now the user domain really consists of the user's
disk, the user's directory, and a lot of times a file,

00:30:55.920 --> 00:30:58.289
I'm sorry, application preferences are stored in there.

00:30:58.289 --> 00:31:03.990
It's also where the, the typical location for a user's
home directory and all the data files are going to be stored.

00:31:03.990 --> 00:31:10.319
And that directory is owned by that
user using the permission structure.

00:31:10.319 --> 00:31:16.569
So the other users can't get in there and get
into the files unless access is given to them.

00:31:16.569 --> 00:31:19.309
Now the next domain up is the computer domain.

00:31:19.309 --> 00:31:25.190
And things can be stored in the computer domain that are
really read only for all of the users on the computer.

00:31:25.190 --> 00:31:32.420
So that may be resources such as fonts, or screen saver, or
any types of files that you distribute out of the computer

00:31:32.420 --> 00:31:35.220
that all the users of that computer would need.

00:31:35.220 --> 00:31:39.600
And once again, that would have the ability
for, the permissions would be set on that

00:31:39.599 --> 00:31:43.250
for all users to be able to access that directory.

00:31:43.250 --> 00:31:50.470
Now third is the system directory, which
mainly is reserved for operating system,

00:31:50.470 --> 00:31:54.900
and operating system update files that
would be put into that system file.

00:31:54.900 --> 00:31:59.220
It's really an area that you don't want to change,
you don't want to delete files out of there,

00:31:59.220 --> 00:32:01.110
you don't want to just generally add things.

00:32:01.109 --> 00:32:07.079
And in most cases it is very, very well protected
from a typical user, and they won't be able to put

00:32:07.079 --> 00:32:11.949
in anything unless they've got some
type of an admin access to the machine.

00:32:11.950 --> 00:32:13.910
So it's really for Apple provided software.

00:32:13.910 --> 00:32:18.769
Now the fourth is really interesting,
