Well that's what a bundle is.

00:33:18.079 --> 00:33:26.029
It has a specific bundle bit set on that folder, and so
it presents that directory or that folder as a single icon

00:33:26.029 --> 00:33:28.849
that can be double clicked or dragged somewhere.

00:33:28.849 --> 00:33:33.139
And now what's inside that bundle is
really another entire folder structure.

00:33:33.140 --> 00:33:38.250
So in the case of an application, you may
have system resources, code resources,

00:33:38.250 --> 00:33:44.400
there may be a folder structure inside that contains
all the graphics that are used in that application.

00:33:44.400 --> 00:33:49.759
So it's a very convenient way, and a very unique way in the
Mac platform to take all of those resources and put them

00:33:49.759 --> 00:33:55.059
into a single icon that can be moved
or distributed in a very easy way.

00:33:55.059 --> 00:34:03.129
And we'll talk about that in another slide, but one of
the things we also do is if you've ever used Keynote,

00:34:03.130 --> 00:34:07.560
obviously you've seen Keynote presentations,
because we're doing those all today.

00:34:07.559 --> 00:34:10.489
But a Keynote file really is also a bundle.

00:34:10.489 --> 00:34:12.449
So a document can also be a bundle.

00:34:12.449 --> 00:34:19.279
It's really a directory that has all the Keynote
data that needs to present the Keynote presentation,

00:34:19.280 --> 00:34:24.070
but then any movies or graphics
that are applied to that slideshow,

00:34:24.070 --> 00:34:26.720
those can be stored right inside that file bundle.

00:34:26.719 --> 00:34:34.939
And it's not just a garbled mess of binary bits
inside there that you'd find in a typical file.

00:34:34.940 --> 00:34:43.730
What you'd see if you looked inside that bundle is that
you'd see the actual dot TIFF files, the dot PNG files.

00:34:43.730 --> 00:34:48.960
So very easy to pull those resources out
if you need to, or add a resource back in,

00:34:48.960 --> 00:34:51.059
if you had to rescue a file for some reason.

00:34:51.059 --> 00:35:00.079
Okay. Next we're going to talk about directory services.

00:35:00.079 --> 00:35:06.239
And directory services over the last really five
years, you know, some people more than that,

00:35:06.239 --> 00:35:12.649
people have been using directory services as a really
nice way to make their networks and their machines,

00:35:12.650 --> 00:35:17.740
all the machines on their networks much more efficient,
and a much better way to manage their systems.

00:35:17.739 --> 00:35:21.709
So it's no different on Mac OS X,
but we'll take a look at how each

00:35:21.710 --> 00:35:26.329
of the specific platforms once again
handles those directory services.

00:35:26.329 --> 00:35:30.230
So they're great at consolidating account information,
because I can handle all of that on the back end,

00:35:30.230 --> 00:35:33.940
I have one place where I can modify
user accounts, things like that.

00:35:33.940 --> 00:35:38.039
And it's great because I only have also
one place to back up those user accounts,

00:35:38.039 --> 00:35:43.050
rather than having individual user accounts stored on
every single computer, that if I wanted to add one I'd have

00:35:43.050 --> 00:35:49.460
to visit every computer, or figure out some way
to add that account on every computer remotely.

00:35:49.460 --> 00:35:56.369
It's also great because you can have just, well some
people would have just a single source place to do that,

00:35:56.369 --> 00:36:02.029
but in most directory systems you've got the
concept of backups, or in the Mac OS X replicas,

00:36:02.030 --> 00:36:08.350
so that you can not only have backups, live backups of that
data running, but also it provides load balancing as well.

00:36:08.349 --> 00:36:10.650
So when you've got a lot of authentications to be performed,

00:36:10.650 --> 00:36:14.530
and those can be pretty CPU taxing,
that handles that as well.

00:36:14.530 --> 00:36:20.320
And you'll find that most people are
doing this around the LDAP standard.

00:36:20.320 --> 00:36:22.300
So how does Microsoft do it?

00:36:22.300 --> 00:36:24.480
Well, you're probably pretty used to active directory,

00:36:24.480 --> 00:36:28.250
it's pretty hard to go somewhere
and not hear about active directory.

00:36:28.250 --> 00:36:32.860
But it's really based around the
concepts of, and really is based on LDAP,

00:36:32.860 --> 00:36:38.470
and some modified Kerberos thrown
in for the authentication pieces.

00:36:38.469 --> 00:36:43.419
And it's primarily administered by the active
directory users and computers application.

00:36:43.420 --> 00:36:47.360
And they use a little bit of a custom
scheme to do their own things that are,

00:36:47.360 --> 00:36:50.200
that apply specifically to the Windows platform.

00:36:50.199 --> 00:36:57.179
So, Unix is a little bit different because you've got the
concept of probably a lot more directory systems out there

00:36:57.179 --> 00:37:02.849
that you tie into, in fact some people may even write their
own directory systems if something doesn't fit their need.

00:37:02.849 --> 00:37:08.940
That's just how handy you know,
Unix admins and Unix people are.

00:37:08.940 --> 00:37:12.010
But typically a lot of those are based on LDAP as well.

00:37:12.010 --> 00:37:18.500
But what's difficult about that platform is
that you may have a system administrator leave,

00:37:18.500 --> 00:37:23.030
and they may have the only knowledge
about how that directory system works.

00:37:23.030 --> 00:37:27.620
And typically every one of them is going to work completely
differently, they're going to have different applications,

00:37:27.619 --> 00:37:34.889
and different tools and commands that they're going to
use to administer that particular directly system.

00:37:34.889 --> 00:37:41.670
Okay, so let's take a little bit, a
look at how that's done on the Mac.

00:37:41.670 --> 00:37:45.909
Some things are very similar, but you'll
see that some things are very different.

00:37:45.909 --> 00:37:48.809
Our solution is based on Open LDAP.

00:37:48.809 --> 00:37:54.900
So open source implementation of an LDAP
server, and we call it Open Directory.

00:37:54.900 --> 00:38:02.450
Now that term Open Directory applies to both the
client, as well as a lot of the concepts on the server.

00:38:02.449 --> 00:38:07.509
But the one thing that's nice about Open Directory is
that it's a very convenient, and very consistent way

00:38:07.510 --> 00:38:15.170
to handle directory services, whether
it is on the client or the server.

00:38:15.170 --> 00:38:23.309
So Open Directory is also a term that we
use to talk about whether the, how the,

00:38:23.309 --> 00:38:26.049
what state the server is in, or what type of a server it is.

00:38:26.050 --> 00:38:32.620
And on the Mac we call that an Open Directory master, and
that's where it would be hosting the entire LDAP directory,

00:38:32.619 --> 00:38:36.789
as well as all the authentication information.

00:38:36.789 --> 00:38:42.269
Now being bound to an Open Directory
server is how we describe the client.

00:38:42.269 --> 00:38:49.059
So using that directory access utility, you would go in and
bind the client to the server, and you have the concept then

00:38:49.059 --> 00:38:53.690
of Open Directory from the server,
and Open Directory on the client.

00:38:53.690 --> 00:39:00.050
And as Jason mentioned, it's an entire plug in
architecture, so if somebody wants to write a plug

00:39:00.050 --> 00:39:03.180
in for our Open Directory architecture, they can do that,

00:39:03.179 --> 00:39:08.589
and that can tie into another completely
different directory system, such as Novell

00:39:08.590 --> 00:39:13.559
or some of the other ones out on
the market if they needed to.

00:39:13.559 --> 00:39:18.880
So to sum up on the directory service tools,
server admin and workgroup manager we've shown you,

00:39:18.880 --> 00:39:25.430
and directory utility we showed you as
well, it's a plug in based architecture.

00:39:25.429 --> 00:39:30.619
And then what we haven't mentioned are some
of the command line tools, and that is a DSCL,

00:39:30.619 --> 00:39:37.239
or directory services command line, and also lookup D. If
you're doing any serious directory services work on the Mac,

00:39:37.239 --> 00:39:42.809
you're probably going to run into those tools, and there
are actually a couple more that we won't get into.

00:39:42.809 --> 00:39:45.889
But that's probably what you're going to use.

00:39:45.889 --> 00:39:53.379
Okay, the next concept is client management.

00:39:53.380 --> 00:39:59.710
And just like directory services, client
management has a lot of people to do,

00:39:59.710 --> 00:40:03.730
to be much more efficient with their client administration.

00:40:03.730 --> 00:40:10.639
And it's a great way to define who is able
to do what, and you find those IT policies

00:40:10.639 --> 00:40:14.159
that you're going to push out to the
systems around the network.

00:40:15.420 --> 00:40:25.559
So for the ability to define what capabilities an
application has, where a user is going to store certain data,

00:40:25.559 --> 00:40:31.820
enforcing those IT policies, maybe
determining whether somebody has the ability

00:40:31.820 --> 00:40:34.990
to burn a CD on that computer or not.

00:40:34.989 --> 00:40:40.879
And generally those are, while they can be set locally,
generally those are going to be pushed out in mass numbers

00:40:40.880 --> 00:40:44.680
from a directory service which we just mentioned.

00:40:44.679 --> 00:40:48.419
So let's take a quick look at how Windows does this.

