00:41:19.199 --> 00:41:25.199
over the operating system, and unless you're an expert,
which many people are, and they know where every single one

00:41:25.199 --> 00:41:33.839
of those files lives and exactly how to edit that particular
flavor of config file, you've also got problems in there

00:41:33.840 --> 00:41:36.220
because it's very, it can be very difficult.

00:41:36.219 --> 00:41:39.859
So what you've really got on the Unix
platform is what you used to have on Windows

00:41:39.860 --> 00:41:42.769
with all the ini files, and all that mess.

00:41:42.769 --> 00:41:47.300
So you know what a pain that can be.

00:41:47.300 --> 00:41:49.350
So how do we do it on the Mac?

00:41:49.349 --> 00:41:56.190
Well long time ago when, oh geez, it's
what six years now, seems so long.

00:41:56.190 --> 00:42:03.559
When Mac OS X was being formed, you know, we, the
engineers, Apple engineers had the ability to look

00:42:03.559 --> 00:42:10.150
at what everybody else had done in the Unix world and
Windows, and they had the ability to see how not to do it,

00:42:10.150 --> 00:42:14.210
and to see well, maybe we should
try to do some things like this.

00:42:14.210 --> 00:42:21.030
And so they had the ability to say well we should
really use some structured configuration files,

00:42:21.030 --> 00:42:26.640
we should store them in various central locations, very
easy to find, most of the files all go in this one spot,

00:42:26.639 --> 00:42:30.000
and they made them all be the same
format, which is a P list,

00:42:30.000 --> 00:42:34.210
what we call a P list format, which
